Introduction
Now you’ll be diving deeper on how to use ZEPETOScript to implement different features for the World you will create by the end of this campaign. In this quest, you will learn the fundamentals of ZEPETOScript required to create and modify GameObjects, move 3D objects and call basic functions. Before starting on this quest, make sure you have completed the previous quest with all the necessary installations settled!
For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the #quest-help channel and quote (C49Q5) when asking your question.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will have:
  • Familiarized yourself with the comparison between C# and TypeScript
  • Created a GameObject and added GameObject Components
  • Rotated a 3D Object
  • Understood the different types of Event Functions and when to use them

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Comparison between C# and TypeScript
In World development, one of the most commonly used programming languages is C#. However, when creating ZEPETO World, we won’t be using C#. You might be wondering if we don’t use C#, what other language is used for creating ZEPETO Worlds? Instead of C#, we will use TypeScript to implement functionality and logic into creating a World. 
TypeScript may be an unfamiliar programming language to learn about compared to C#. But they have more in common than you might think. To ease your learning journey into TypeScript, watch the video below to understand the differences between TypeScript and C#. The video covers a side by side comparison on lets and const, primitive types, enums, arrays and tuples.



Feel free to go through these other resources to familiarize yourself more with TypeScript:
  • TypeScript - The Basics
  • Why C# goes well with TypeScript - Nate Hill

Don’t worry if you still don’t feel 100% comfortable with TypeScript. Throughout the process of creating a ZEPETO World, the code needed to implement the basic functionalities are written in the steps as you go through each of the quests.

Step 3: Rotate a 3D Object
Now that you know how GameObjects and Components work in ZEPETOScript, let’s learn how to control an object’s movement with ZEPETOScript by implementing a rotating cube.
In the same project as Step 1, create a 3D Cube by right clicking under the Hierarchy window and selecting 3D Object > Cube. A Cube is a primitive type of GameObject just like other 3D Objects such as a Sphere, Plane, and Cylinder. Create a new TypeScript file in the Assets folder and rename it to RotatorScript. Open up the TypeScript file and name the script the same name as your file.

In RotatorScript.ts, declare and initialize variables representing the rotation speed for dimensions X, Y, and Z to the values 0.5, 0, and 0 respectively. The declaration and initialization of variables should follow the syntax below:

AccessModifier propertyName: propertyType = propertyValue;

Below the declarations, instead of calling a Start function, call a new event function called Update function. A Start function is called right when the script is enabled, whereas Update function is executed once for every frame. This means that the code inside the Update function is constantly being executed every time the script runs. You will learn more about event functions in the next step of this quest.

Inside the Update function, type the following code to implement a rotation of the GameObject it will be attached to. What that line of code means is that every frame would rotate at a rate of 0.5 in the x-axis direction. The greater the value, the faster the object would rotate in that direction. You can find the full code in the Working Code section.

Return to your project and attach RotatorScript.ts to the Cube. Click the Play button and make sure that the Cube is rotating in the x-axis direction. Take a screenshot of your cube rotating, just like what you see in “Expected Output”. 

Your screenshot should show:
  • Your full screen, including your taskbar (for Windows) / dock (for MacOS)
  • A new GameObject created when the project is running
  • The Cube’s Components under the Inspector window
  • Make sure that all parts visible in “Expected Output” are also visible in your screenshot(s)!

Rename your screenshot “C49_Q5_yourStackUpName.png”, where yourStackUpName is your StackUp profile name.
Working code
import { ZepetoScriptBehaviour } from 'ZEPETO.Script' export default class RotatorScript extends ZepetoScriptBehaviour {   public rotationSpeedX : number = 0.5;   public rotationSpeedY : number = 0;   public rotationSpeedZ : number = 0;   Update() {     this.transform.Rotate(this.rotationSpeedX, this.rotationSpeedY, this.rotationSpeedZ);   } }
Expected output
Step 4: Event Functions
You have already used Start and Update functions so far. These types of functions are called event functions. Event functions are a critical part of scripting which allows the script to respond to events in the World by calling a specific event function.
Click here to learn more about the different event functions that are important for developing a ZEPETO World. Take the time to understand and try implementing the following event functions:
  • Start()
  • Update(), FixedUpdate(), LateUpdate()
  • Awake()
  • OnGUI()
  • OnCollisionEnter(), OnCollisionStay(), OnCollisionExit()
  • OnTriggerEnter(), OnTriggerStay(), OnTriggerExit()
  • OnEnable(), OnDisable()
  • OnDestroy(), OnApplicationQuit()
